JavaScript Silent Errors:

- JavaScript can fail siently. A silent error will not stop your program. The execution will continue.
- The reason for silent errors is historical: The first version of JavaScript did not have
    catch...try exceptions.
- ☠️ Silent errors are issues that do not throw exceptions or stop execution, but still cause logic
    bugs, unexpected behavior, or failures that are easy to miss.
    eg:
        let x = 1 / 0;
        document.getElementById("demo").innerHTML = x;  // Infinity

        let result = "Not Active.";
        let isActive = false;
        if (isActive = true) {   // ❌ Assignment, not comparison
            let result = "Active!";
        }
        document.getElementById("demo").innerHTML = result; // Not Active.

- Many numeric operations that fail produce NaN (not an exception).
    JavaScript will not crash. It just quietly gives you NaN and keeps going.

        const result = parseInt("abc");
        // NaN - no error, just wrong data
        document.getElementById("demo").innerHTML = result;     // NaN

- Accessing a missing property just returns undefined silently.

        const user = {};
        let result = user.name;
        document.getElementById("demo").innerHTML = result;     // undefined

- JavaScript coerces types differently per operator. Type coercion hides bugs. Program continues,
    but logic is wrong.

        let result1 = ('5' + '2');
        let result2 = ('5' - '2');
        document.getElementById("demo").innerHTML = result1 + "<br>" + result2;

